==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|acoustumer|lang=fro}}, {{term|acustumer|lang=fro}} (Modern French {{term|accoutumer|lang=fr}}) corresponding to {{term|a||to, toward|lang=fro}} + {{term|coustume|lang=fro|custom}}. More at {{term|custom|lang=en}}, {{term|costume|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ə.ˈkəs.təm/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-accustom.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To make familiar by use; to cause to accept; to habituate, familiarize, or inure; -- with ''to''.
#* ca. '''1753''', {{w|John Hawkesworth}} et al., ''Adventurer''
#*: I shall always fear that he who '''accustoms''' himself to fraud in little things, wants only opportunity to practice it in greater.
#* {{quote-book|year=1910|author={{w|Emerson Hough}}
|title=[http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/11593 The Purchase Price]|chapter=1
|passage=“[…] it is not fair of you to bring against mankind double weapons&thinsp;! Dangerous enough you are as woman alone, without bringing to your aid those gifts of mind suited to problems which men have been '''accustomed''' to arrogate to themselves.”}}
# {{context|intransitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To be [[wont]].
#: {{rfquotek|Carew}}
# {{context|intransitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[cohabit]].
#* {{w|John Milton}}
#*: We with the best men '''accustom''' openly; you with the basest commit private adulteries.

